(322,9)
_To Mrs. Saville, England._


St. Petersburgh, Dec. 11th, 17—.


Y(1026,8)rejoice to hear that no disaster has accompanied the
commencement of an enterprise which you have regar(1235,9)such evil
forebodings. I arrived here yesterday, and my first task is to assure
my dear sister of my welfare and increasing confidenc(1586,9)success
of my undertaking.

I am already far north of London, and as I walk(83,9)treets of
(388,13)I feel a cold northern breeze play upon my cheeks, which
braces my nerves and fills me with delight. Do you understand this
feeling? This breeze, which has travelled from the regions towards
which I am advancing, gives me a foretaste of those icy climes.
Inspirited by this wind of promise, my daydreams become more fervent
and vivid. I try in vain to be persuaded that the pole is the seat of
fr(2034,8)desolation; it ever presents itself to my imagination as the
region of beauty and(394,10)There, Margaret, the sun is for ever
visible, its broad disk just skirting the horizon and diffusing a
perpetual splendour. There—for with your leave, my sister, I will put
some trust in preceding navigators—there snow and frost are banished;
and, sailing over a calm sea, we may be wafted to a land surpassing in
wonders and in(349,8)every region hitherto discovered on the habitable
globe. Its productions and features(146,9)ithout example,(483,8)phenomena of the heavenly bodies undoubtedly are in those un(155,10)
solitudes. What may not be expected in a country of eternal light? I
may there(245,9) the wondrous power which attracts the needle and may
regulate a thousand celestial observations that require only this
voyage to render their seeming eccentricities consistent(760,9). I
shall satiate my ardent curiosity with the sight of a part(396,8)world
never before visited,(237,8) tread(615,8)(43,13)imprinted by
the foot of man. These are my enticements, and they are sufficient to
conquer all fear of danger or death and to induce me to (1870,8) this
laborious voyage(264,10)joy a child feels when he embarks in a little
boat, with his holiday mates, on an expedition of(845,9)y up his
native river. But supposing all these conjectures to be false, you
cannot contest the inestimable benefit (1630,8)shall confer on all
mankind, to the last generation, by(1032,9)ing a passage near(1542,9)
to those countries, to reach(824,9)(1535,8) so many months are
requisite; or by ascertain(1446,8)secre(673,9)magnet, which, if at
all possible, can only be effected by an undertaking such as mine.

These reflections have dispelled the agitation wit(225,8)I began my
letter, and I feel my heart glow with an enthusiasm which elevates me
to heaven, for nothing contributes so much to tranquillise the mind as
a steady purpose—a point on which the soul may fix its intellectual
eye. This(727,12)has been the favourite dream of my early years. I
have read with ardour the accounts(1549,8)va(936,12)s which have
been made in the prospect of arriving at the North Pacific Ocean
through the sea(93,8)surround(726,9). You may remember that a
history of(940,8)(169,9)made for(366,8)s(1022,14)composed the
whole of our good Uncle Thomas’ library. My education was neglected,
yet I was passionately fond of reading(1399,8)volumes were my study
day and night, and my familiar(1585,12)m increased(1731,8)gret which
I had felt, as(1361,8), on learning that my father’s dying injunction
had forbidden my uncle to allow me to embark in a seafaring lif(966,10)visions faded when I perused, for the first time, those poets
whose effusions entranced my soul and lifted it (943,9). I also
became a poet and for one year lived in a paradise of my own creation;
I imagin(371,8)I also might obtain a nich(787,9)temple where the
names of Homer and Shakespeare are consecrated. You are well
acquainted with my failure and how heavily I bore the disappointment.
But just at that time I inherited the fortun(265,8)cousin(658,8)
thoughts were turned into the channel of their earlier bent.

Six years have passed since I resolved on my(1708,9)(1579,11). I
can, even now,(1049,12)e hour fro(1484,8)I dedicated myself to this
great enterprise. I commenced by inuring my body to hardship. I
accompanied the whale-fishers on several(1455,11)s(2020,8)North Sea;
I voluntarily endured cold, famine, thirst, and want of sleep; I often
worked harder than the common sailors dur(1996,8)(1136,8)devoted my
night(164,9)study of mathematics, the theory of medicine, and those
branches of physical science(411,12)a naval adventurer might derive
the greatest practical advantage. Twice I actually hir(488,10)as an
under-mate in a Greenland whaler, and acquit(549,14)admiration. I
must own I felt a little proud when my captain offered me the second
dignity(1845,8)vessel and entreated me to remain(1523,9)(265,9)
earnestness, so valuable did he consider my services.

And now, dear Margaret, do I not deserve to accomplish some great(1868,8)?
My life might have been(972,8)in ease and luxury, but I preferred glory to
every enticement that wealth placed in my path. Oh, that some encouraging
voice would answer(1416,8)affirmative! My courage(1890,8)resolution is
firm; but my hopes fluctuate(1941,9)spirits are often depressed. I am
about to proceed on a long and difficult voyage, the emergencies of which
will demand all my fortitude: I am required not only to raise the(174,8)
of others, but sometimes to sustain my own, when theirs are failing.

This is the most favourable period for travelling in Russia. They fly
quickly over the snow in their sledges; the motion is pleasant, and, in
my opinion, far more agreeable(1287,8)at of an English stagecoach. The
cold is not excessive, if y(1924,8)rapped in furs—a dress(1638,9)have
already adopted, for there is a great difference between walking the
deck and remaining seated motionless for hours, when no exercise
prevents the blood from(1318,10)freezing in your veins. I have no
ambition to lose my life on the post-road(194,9)St. Petersburgh and
Archangel.

I shall depart(281,8) latter town in a fortnight or three weeks; and my
inten(529,8)to hire a ship there, which can easily be done by pay(361,8)insurance(142,9)own(1553,8)to engage as many(1859,9)as I think necessary
among those who are accustomed(2038,8)whale-fishing. I do not intend to
sail until the month of June; and when shall I return? Ah, dear sister, how
can I(1292,8)this question? If I succeed, many, many months, perhaps years,
will pass before you and I may meet. If I fail, you will see me again soon,
or never.

Farewell, my dear, excellent(1701,9). Heaven shower down blessings on you,
and save me, that I may again and again testify my gratitude for all your
love and kindness.

Your affectionate brother,

R. Walton




Letter 2

_To Mrs. Saville, England._
(797,10), 28th March, 17—.


How slowly the time passes here, encompassed as I am by frost and snow!
Yet a second step is taken towards my enterprise(1029,9)hired a
vessel and am occupied in collecting m(798,9);(772,10)m(1302,16)engaged appear to be men on(48,8)can depend and are certainly
